<paragraph blockId="40.[151,1437,153,1655]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1448,1475]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Machado &amp; Oswald, 2020" authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" box="[341,556,1449,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Csiroleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[341,556,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Csiroleon fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[562,650,1449,1475]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[562,650,1449,1475]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is clearly related to 
<taxonomicName box="[872,1049,1449,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Csiroleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumidipalpus">
<emphasis box="[872,1049,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">C. tumidipalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; both share the extremely elongate labial palpi, which seems to be unique among 
<taxonomicName box="[661,851,1485,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="72" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Dendroleontinae">Dendroleontinae</taxonomicName>
. Pretarsal claws, ocular setae, and terminalia are also very similar in both species. Despite these shared similarities, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" box="[839,971,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Csiroleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[839,971,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">C. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Csiroleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tumidipalpus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">C. tumidipalpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the much paler body, hyaline wings, reduced number of elongate setae on legs and mesonotum, and particularly by the banded pattern of the abdomen. The description of this new species is justified by all of these characters, despite the fact that the males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Machado &amp; Oswald" authorityYear="2020" box="[520,653,1629,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Csiroleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[520,653,1629,1655]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">C. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are still unknown. For phylogenetic relationships see 
<figureCitation box="[1259,1327,1629,1655]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1373,1398]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,348,1348]" captionTargetId="figure@30.[151,1436,345,1348]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 4. Strict consensus tree of morphology-based parsimony analysis of species belonging to the former subtribe Periclystina (ingroup, names in black), and outgroups (names in red). Former Glenoleon species are shown on blue branches, former Austrogymnocnemia species on green branches. Numbers above branches are Bremer support values; numbers below branches are bootstrap values (shown where&gt;50%)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3896822" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3896822/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
